More than 58 % of the world's coral reefs are endangered because of pollution, the over-harvesting of reef fish and other human factors.
Farther south, scientists found that serious concentrations of a blue-green algae known as cyanobacterium are killing corals and other reef organisms.
In 1998, an El Nino global coral bleaching event caused deaths of many coral reefs, a disaster occurring only once in 1,000 years.
It noted that coral on many Caribbean reefs have declined by up to 80 %, and many reefs do not resemble the reefs of 30 years ago.
